00:52:52.240 --> 00:52:53.990
PhD in AI does not mean you know how to

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.309
code. Having access to an LLM also does

00:52:56.319 --> 00:52:58.069
not mean you know how to code. Thinking

00:52:58.079 --> 00:52:59.589
that either of these do is probably a

00:52:59.599 --> 00:53:01.430
negative signal in general. Being a

00:53:01.440 --> 00:53:03.030
programmer is harder than being good.

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:04.470
Being a good programmer is harder than

00:53:04.480 --> 00:53:06.630
being good at AI. Every good programmer

00:53:06.640 --> 00:53:08.230
who has started doing RL with us has

00:53:08.240 --> 00:53:10.870
done very well. Most of programming is

00:53:10.880 --> 00:53:13.030
very simple. Simple does not mean easy.

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:14.549
The thing that makes programming hard is

00:53:14.559 --> 00:53:15.990
that it is often terribly taught in a

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:17.589
way that trains you to over complicate

00:53:17.599 --> 00:53:19.670
everything. unlearning this takes either

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:21.190
years of failure and pain or a

00:53:21.200 --> 00:53:23.430
particularly open mind. Your entire

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:24.790
outlook on how to program could be

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:26.790
stupid and wrong. If you're brand new to

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:28.630
programming, you have an advantage here.

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:29.990
If you are not new but are reading this

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:31.430
