00:54:14.390 --> 00:54:14.400
Programming is the act of writing down

00:54:14.400 --> 00:54:16.470
instructions that operate on data. The

00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:17.990
list of instructions is relatively

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.069
short. Create variables by assigning

00:54:20.079 --> 00:54:22.069
data to addresses in memory. Evaluate

00:54:22.079 --> 00:54:23.750
conditions on variables. Loop over

00:54:23.760 --> 00:54:25.109
conditions to run the same set of

00:54:25.119 --> 00:54:26.870
instructions many times. Group

00:54:26.880 --> 00:54:28.790
instructions together into functions.

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:30.309
Can learn the tools of the trade within

00:54:30.319 --> 00:54:32.230
a few hours. But apply applying them

00:54:32.240 --> 00:54:33.510
effectively is the pursuit of a

00:54:33.520 --> 00:54:35.990
lifetime. Skill in programming is not is

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.150
not logarithmic. A bad programmer

00:54:38.160 --> 00:54:39.990
creates problems. A good programmer

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.069
solves problems. A great programmer can

00:54:42.079 --> 00:54:43.270
change the world with nothing more than

00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:45.349
a laptop. Enough philosophy. Here are my

00:54:45.359 --> 00:54:47.750
top 10 suggestions.

00:54:47.760 --> 00:54:49.910
Learn by doing. Start with something

00:54:49.920 --> 00:54:51.750
that will take you a few hours. Build up

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:53.190
to something that will take you a few

00:54:53.200 --> 00:54:56.230
days. Simple games are great because you

00:54:56.240 --> 00:54:58.790
get a quick feel, a a quick visual

00:54:58.800 --> 00:55:00.309
feedback. Wait, because you get quick

00:55:00.319 --> 00:55:02.390
visual feedback for most problems. I'd

00:55:02.400 --> 00:55:04.150
suggest using Ray for rendering.

00:55:04.160 --> 00:55:05.589
Lightweight, available in nearly every

00:55:05.599 --> 00:55:07.349
language. The library itself is a great

00:55:07.359 --> 00:55:09.829
example of well-designed software. Start

00:55:09.839 --> 00:55:12.150
with Python. A lot of experienced devs

00:55:12.160 --> 00:55:14.390
hate Python. I sometimes hate Python,

00:55:14.400 --> 00:55:16.069
too. You should start with Python

00:55:16.079 --> 00:55:18.230
anyways because it will let you get

00:55:18.240 --> 00:55:20.230
started faster than almost anything

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:22.549
else. Most AI projects you encounter

00:55:22.559 --> 00:55:24.150
will have at least the top layer written

00:55:24.160 --> 00:55:28.069
in it. But don't spend too long in let's

00:55:28.079 --> 00:55:30.470
Python here. But don't spend too long in

00:55:30.480 --> 00:55:32.710
Python. Design of a language pushes you

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:34.390
towards a specific way of thinking about

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:36.870
problems. Avoid heavy external packages,

00:55:36.880 --> 00:55:38.630
inheritance, checker, decorators, and

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:39.910
generally anything else that takes you

00:55:39.920 --> 00:55:41.910
away from learning to express logic in

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:43.270
terms of assignment conditions and

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:48.309
iteration.

00:55:55.510 --> 00:55:55.520
and functions. Write a couple basic

00:55:55.520 --> 00:55:57.270
games, applications, or tools and move

00:55:57.280 --> 00:56:00.470
on. Use UV for package management. Learn

00:56:00.480 --> 00:56:02.630
C early. C is a wonderfully simple

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:04.549
language for writing high performance

00:56:04.559 --> 00:56:06.230
software. The only reason I don't

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:07.670
suggest learning C first is that it

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:09.349
requires you to learn a bit more about

00:56:09.359 --> 00:56:11.589
how computers and operating systems work

00:56:11.599 --> 00:56:13.349
pretty much all at once when you're new.

00:56:13.359 --> 00:56:14.950
A short list of concepts that you

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:16.710
understand types, type cast struck,

00:56:16.720 --> 00:56:18.950
single pass compilation, linking, memory

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:21.190
allocation, stack versus heat point

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:22.870
pointers.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:25.030
Avoid C++ for now. It's C with a ton of

00:56:25.040 --> 00:56:27.109
extra stuff bolted on that you mostly

00:56:27.119 --> 00:56:31.589
don't need.

00:56:49.349 --> 00:56:49.359
Avoid abstraction. Always aim to solve

00:56:49.359 --> 00:56:50.870
the problem at hand in the simplest way

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:52.549
possible.

00:56:52.559 --> 00:56:55.270
Do not introduce complexity for the sake

00:56:55.280 --> 00:56:57.430
of generality unless you know for sure

00:56:57.440 --> 00:56:59.270
that the eventuality you're planning for

00:56:59.280 --> 00:57:01.349
will actually arise. Even then, it is

00:57:01.359 --> 00:57:02.870
often better to beat that horse when it

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:04.870
arrives. C is great for this because it

00:57:04.880 --> 00:57:06.230
takes away most of those tempting

00:57:06.240 --> 00:57:07.910
self-defeating tools like inheritance in

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:13.270
heavy third party libraries.

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:15.200
Use a debugger. A debugger allows you to

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:16.789
run your code line by line and expect

00:57:16.799 --> 00:57:19.190
the value of local variables.

00:57:19.200 --> 00:57:20.950
dramatically faster and more flexible

00:57:20.960 --> 00:57:22.150
than littering your code with print

00:57:22.160 --> 00:57:23.670
statements and allows you to jump around

00:57:23.680 --> 00:57:26.630
quickly. PDB for Python or GDB for C

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:28.549
will suffice. Use an address sanitizer

00:57:28.559 --> 00:57:31.109
for C. This will give you readable error

00:57:31.119 --> 00:57:32.390
messages and is so important that I

00:57:32.400 --> 00:57:34.150
would not suggest C without one. That is

00:57:34.160 --> 00:57:36.390
true.

00:57:36.400 --> 00:57:38.230
Learn basic Unix tooling. Get

00:57:38.240 --> 00:57:40.069
comfortable with the command line ASAP.

00:57:40.079 --> 00:57:42.150
You don't need to be fancy here. Basic

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:45.430
commands like ls, pwd, cat, head, move,

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:49.109
copy, cd, make, d, top, etc. You'll only

00:57:49.119 --> 00:57:51.030
need the top uh the 10 most common

00:57:51.040 --> 00:57:53.510
commands 90% of the time. Ideally, use

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:55.589
native Linux if you can. Mac OS is okay.

00:57:55.599 --> 00:57:57.910
Windows is not. Use WSL if you do want

00:57:57.920 --> 00:57:59.910
if you do not want to do a boot. I'd

00:57:59.920 --> 00:58:02.150
suggest a basic Auntu install. Do not go

00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:03.829
ham customizing everything. Get

00:58:03.839 --> 00:58:05.190
comfortable with your DRO's package

00:58:05.200 --> 00:58:06.549
manager, which is probably going to be

00:58:06.559 --> 00:58:09.829
apt, not snap. Don't get nerd sniped.

